I'll start by executing the first tool in the workflow - the file reader to get our input data.

<tool_call>file_operations_reader
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Now I'll proceed with the next step in the workflow - parsing the data we just read. I'll use the data_processing_parser tool.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            I'll use the file_operations_scanner to detect the format of our input file before attempting to parse it again.

<tool_call>file_operations_scanner
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Since the scanner executed successfully but we need to know the file format, I'll execute the file_operations_scanner again with more detailed options to specifically detect the file format.

<tool_call>file_operations_scanner
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {
    "detailed_scan": true,
    "detect_format": true
  }
}
</tool_call>

            I'll attempt to read the file again with the basic file_operations_reader to verify the file exists and get its raw content, which might help determine the format.

<tool_call>file_operations_reader
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {
    "raw": true
  }
}
</tool_call>

            Based on the successful file read, I'll now attempt to parse the data again, this time explicitly specifying the format as JSON since the file has a .json extension.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {
    "format": "json"
  }
}
</tool_call>

Now that we've successfully parsed the data, I'll proceed with the next step in the workflow - filtering the data. I'll use the data_processing_filter tool.

<tool_call>data_processing_filter
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {
    "filter_rules": {
      "default": "include"
    }
  }
}
</tool_call>
